G-PERSIST-KV-PARITY -- persistent O(1) conversation KV is BYTE-EXACT (2026-06-26)
================================================================================
WHAT: the daemon's #1 slowdown fix. run_kvdecode_chat now REUSES the resident KV across
turns: when the committed sequence (prev prompt + the tokens generated last turn) is a STRICT
PREFIX of this turn's prompt AND the cache position equals its length, it prefills ONLY the new
suffix instead of reset(0) + re-prefilling the whole conversation. Engine tools/sp_daemon
src/routes.rs; default-off env SP_PERSIST_KV; PLAIN decode path only (gated out of recall /
agency / replay / inject / single_entry, all of which reset or rebuild the cache, so the
committed sequence is guaranteed to mirror the cache).

GATE (real gemma4-12b-b1.sp-model, port 3001, temperature 0, byteexact default-on):
 A 2-turn conversation -- turn 2 appends a new user message to turn 1. Identical script run
 against two daemons (persist ON vs OFF).
   ON  (SP_PERSIST_KV=1):  daemon log =>
       "PERSIST-KV: reuse 32 committed tokens; prefill suffix 21 (full would be 53)"
   OFF (env unset):        0 PERSIST-KV reuse lines  (pure null floor: reset + full re-prefill)
   turn-2 answer SHA-256:
       ON  2D1C3BCC447F83021C70DDC0DFEA9E5BAFC83EFCD787B2A44526777E78CFA9B4
       OFF 2D1C3BCC447F83021C70DDC0DFEA9E5BAFC83EFCD787B2A44526777E78CFA9B4
   => BYTE-IDENTICAL: True.

WHY BYTE-EXACT: the reused prefix's K/V is the SAME deterministic computation whether it was
prefilled last turn or re-prefilled this turn; only the new suffix is prefilled fresh -- exactly
what a full re-prefill would compute. So reuse == full-prefill bit-for-bit (the byteexact /
exact-integer forward already gives run-to-run bit-identity, which is what makes this provable).

THE WIN: turn-2 prefill dropped 53 -> 21 tokens here. The reuse GROWS with conversation length:
in a 3000-turn chat the committed prefix is ~the entire transcript, so the daemon prefills only
the new ~20-token turn => O(new turn), not O(conversation). This is the structural fix for the
"snappy at first, 30+ tok/s -> <=1, 5 min at 3000 turns" slowdown -- the per-turn prefill no
longer re-pays the whole history. (Decode still attends over the live KV; for the plain / agent
path that IS the real context. The daemon-recall config -- which resets the cache and so cannot
use persist -- stays bounded by the console context-window cap W=24.)

SAFETY / NULL FLOOR: env unset => prefill_from stays 0 => byte-identical to reset+full-prefill
(the OFF run proves it: 0 reuse, identical SHA-256). The fast path fires ONLY when committed is a
strict prefix AND cache pos == committed.len(); it FAILS CLOSED on any divergence (e.g. a
response that re-tokenizes differently) or any external cache change -> full reset + prefill.
Restricted to the plain decode path so no recall/agency side-call can desync committed from cache.

REPRO:
  tests\perf\_persist_serve.bat 1            (daemon: SP_PERSIST_KV=1, plain decode, :3001)
  python tests\perf\_g_persist_kv_parity.py on
  (stop daemon)
  tests\perf\_persist_serve.bat              (daemon: persist OFF -- no arg)
  python tests\perf\_g_persist_kv_parity.py off
  Get-FileHash _persist_r2_on.txt, _persist_r2_off.txt   -> equal hashes = PASS

USAGE (live): persist applies to the PLAIN / agent decode path. Run the daemon plain
(_persist_serve.bat 1 -- no SP_B3_JUDGE/auto_recall/SP_DECIDE/SP_FORGET/SP_B4_NIGHTSHIFT) and let
the harness agent (run_gateway.bat) manage memory via tools; the console then gets O(1) full
context. Build: cargo build --release --features wire_cuda_backend (29.6s, BUILD_EXIT=0).
